For this exam, you will begin creating a React web application for a fictional online store called *MultiShop* that sells products across several categories.  To get started, access and familiarize yourself with the following resources:

* [MultiShop\_template.zip](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Ulim9erk3ZaXA8LyzGpAnEzY8RPSfV-c/view?usp=sharing).  The accompanying Zip file contains the starting HTML/CSS template for the application.  Download this file and familiarize yourself with the pages it contains (inspect the code to see the major page sections denoted by HTML comments).  
* [DummyJSON.com](https://dummyjson.com/):  This is a REST API that contains fake data that the application will use (we’ll focus on the products data).  Read the docs and try out some of the endpoints to familiarize yourself with its functionality.  Install the [JSON formatter](https://chrome.google.com/webstore/detail/json-formatter/bcjindcccaagfpapjjmafapmmgkkhgoa?hl=en) Chrome extension for a better JSON viewing experience.  
1. **App Setup.**  Complete the following to set up the initial app:  
   1. [Use Vite](https://liaogg.medium.com/build-your-next-react-app-with-vite-part-2-6d51b58561c8) to create a new React app called *multi-shop* (hereafter referred to as “the app”).  In the Vite setup menu, choose *React* as the framework and *JavaScript \+ SWC* as the variant.  
   2. Copy the subfolders (/css, /img, /js, /lib, /mail, and /scss) and all their contents from the template into the /public directory of the app.  
   3. To simplify the development process for the exam, all CSS styling will be handled centrally using the files provided by the template.  To import these styles, replace the entire \<head\> element of the index.html file in the app with the head element (and its contents) of the index.html file in the template.  
      1. For all \<link\> elements with relative href paths (those not beginning with https), add an initial forward slash (/) in front of the path (e.g., css/style.css → /css/style.css).  This will ensure that path names are resolved correctly when routing is implemented later.  Note that although these resources are in the public folder, you do **NOT** need to include /public in the path name, as this is handled automatically by the build process.  
   4. At the bottom of the index.html template page (after the footer) is a series of \<script\> elements for various JavaScript libraries.  Copy these into the index.html page of the app in the same location (right before the closing \</body\> tag).  
      1. For all \<script\> elements with relative src paths (those not beginning with https), add an initial forward slash (/) in front of the path (e.g., js/main.js → /js/main.js).  This will ensure that path names are resolved correctly when routing is implemented later. Note that although these resources are in the public folder, you do **NOT** need to include /public in the path name, as this is handled automatically by the build process.  
   5. Create a /components subdirectory in the /src directory of the app  
   6. Delete the default JSX returned in the App component.  Also remove the count state variable and the imports of the React logo and Vite logo.  Finally, remove the import of the app.css file (this file will not be used and can be deleted).  
        
2. **Layout.** Create a /Layout directory within the /components directory. For the overall layout of the app, create the following components in this directory (note that these components will mostly correspond with the major sections denoted by HTML comments in the template pages).  As you create each component, be sure to take the following steps:  
* Change class= to className=  
* Close any self-closing elements (e.g., \<img\>, \<input\>) with /\>.    
* Modify any inline styles to use the JavaScript style names (camel case) and object notation (e.g., 

  style="width: calc(100% \- 30px); z-index: 999;" → *style*\={{width: \`calc(100% \- 30px)\`, zIndex: 999}})

* Remove any HTML comments (or comment them out with JavaScript/JSX comment syntax)  
* (Optional): In hyperlinks, replace href=”” and href=”\#” with href=”/” (this will prevent you from getting warnings about invalid links when running the app.)  
  1. Create *TopBar*, *NavBar*, and *Footer* components that return the content of the corresponding sections in the index.html template.  
     1. Change the href attribute value of the MultiShop logo and the Home link (in NavBar) to “/”  
  2. Create a *Layout* wrapper component that renders an instance of the *TopBar*, *NavBar*, and *Footer* components.  Render any children props between *NavBar* and *Footer*.  
  3. Create a *Container* wrapper component, which will serve as a generic configurable container component for use throughout the app.  This component should render a single \<div\> element, and should set the className property of this div to a value received via props.  The component should render its children prop inside of this div.  
  4. In the *App* component, render an instance of the *Layout* component.

3. **CategoryMenu.** The categories drop-down menu in the *NavBar* displays a static list of categories.  Make this menu dynamic by completing the following:  
   1. Inside the /components directory, create a new /Categories subdirectory.  There, create a separate *CategoryMenu* component that contains the content of the Category Menu (denoted with comments in index.html of the template).  Replace the code for the category menu in the NavBar component with an instance of the *CategoryMenu* component.  
   2. Modify the *CategoryMenu* component to display category names retrieved from the DummyJSON API instead of hard-coded values.  The component should make an API call once when the component is loaded.  Consider formatting the category names so they look nicer (capitalize letters and replace dashes with spaces).  Each link in the list should point to /products/category/\[category name\], where \[category name\] is the name of the respective category.  
        
4. **CategoryList.** In the /components/Categories directory, create a new *CategoryList* component.  This component should look like the Categories section of the index.html template page.  Implement the following:  
   1. The component should show category names, images, and number of products using data pulled from the DummyJSON API. **Hint:** because the /products/categories API endpoint does not include images or number of products, consider retrieving the list of all products from the API, and then creating a new array with only one product (any one will do) for each category.  You can use that product’s thumbnail for the category image.  (Add a limit=0 query string argument to the API request to ensure you get all products back). You can also count the number of products in each category.  
   2. The link of each category should point to /products/category/\[category name\], where \[category name\] is the name of the respective category.  
   3. In the App component, add basic routing logic (based on window.location.pathname) to render the CategoryList inside of Layout if the pathname \= /categories.  Modify the “Shop” link in the NavBar to point to this path.

   This tile is used in several places in the template, such as the Featured Products section of the home page and also on the Shop page.  In the index.html template page, one of the tiles is denoted by an HTML comment in the Featured Products section.  
1. Create a /components/Products directory.  In this directory, create a reusable *ProductTile* component that can be reused throughout the application.  The component should accept a product object as a prop and display the product thumbnail, name (title), and price in the appropriate place on each tile.  Each product name should be a link that points to /products/\[id\], where \[id\] is the id of the product.  Ignore the star ratings.  For the strikethrough price, display a value equal to:  
   1.  *price / (1-(discountPercentage/100))*  
2. Each tile begins with a \<div\> element that contains bootstrap class names to configure the tile to display properly  on screens of different sizes:

   

   \<div class="col-lg-3 col-md-4 col-sm-6 pb-1"\>

   

   This indicates, for example, that the div should take 3 columns on large screens (col-lg-3), 4 columns on medium screens (col-md-4), and 6 columns on small screens (col-sm-6).  To make the component configurable in different settings, change this code to dynamically set these classes to a value passed in via props.

      2. A string of classNames for the list itself so that it can be configured. (e.g, \<div class="row px-xl-5"\>  
      3. A string of classNames for the *ProductTile* components that will be forwarded on to those components.  
   2. For each product in the props array, the component should generate an instance of the *ProductTile* component, passing in the product object and the product tile classnames via props.

The component should then reproduce the FeaturedProducts section of the index.html template page, including creating an instance of  the ProductList component, passing in as props the array of products, the class names "row px-xl-5" for the list, and the class names "col-lg-3 col-md-4 col-sm-6 pb-1"

11. **ProductContext.**  Presently, the *CategoryMenu*, *CategoryList*, *FeaturedProducts*, *ProductsByCategory*, and *ProductDetail* components all retrieve data from the DummyJSON API each time the component is loaded.  This means that (a) there are multiple API calls each time a link is clicked (e.g., the *CategoryMenu* reloads every time\!) and (b) each component needs to have its own data fetching functions.  To address these issues, do the following:  
    1. Modify the app architecture by creating a *ProductContext* and a custom *ProductContextProvider* component (in a file called product-context.jsx located within a /store directory) that will be responsible for fetching product and category data for the app, and then providing this data to child components via various functions.  Specifically, this *ProductContextProvider* component should do the following:  
       1. When the component first loads, it should retrieve an array of all products from the browser’s [sessionStorage](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/sessionStorage) (sessionStorage works just like localStorage, except the data only persists while the user’s browser tab is open) and save it in a state variable.  If the data does not exist in sessionStorage, the component should retrieve the data from the API using the /products?limit=0 endpoint, and then save the data in a state variable **and** in sessionStorage for subsequent requests.  (Hint:  sessionStorage stores data in string format, so when adding or retrieving array or object data, use [JSON.stringify()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/JSON/stringify) and [JSON.parse()](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/JSON/parse), respectively.  
       2. The component should include a series of functions for retrieving product and category data.  These functions should **not** make their own API calls, but should instead use the product data retrieved in the previous step using various JavaScript array functions (e.g., forEach, find, filter, etc.).  These functions should include:  
          1. getCategories(): returns an array containing all unique category names along with an image and an id for each category. (Use the same logic to get unique categories from products as implemented in the CategoryList component.)  
          2. getProductsByCategory(category):  returns an array of products in the given category.  
          3. getFeaturedProducts(numProducts): returns an array of *numProducts* products selected from the products list.  (You can fetch the first products in the list or [randomly select](https://bobbyhadz.com/blog/javascript-get-multiple-random-elements-from-array#:~:text=To%20get%20multiple%20random%20elements,to%20get%20multiple%20random%20elements.) products.)  
          4. getProduct(productID): Retrieves a specific product by the given ID  
       3. The component should return a *ProductContext.Provider* component with pointers to these functions in its *value* prop.  
    2. In the App component, modify the returned JSX by enclosing the *Layout* component inside of an instance of the *ProductContextProvider* component.  This will make the provider and its data available to all child components.  
    3. In the *CategoryMenu*, *CategoryList*, *FeaturedProducts*, *ProductsByCategory*, and *ProductDetail* components, remove all the data fetching and state management code.  Instead, retrieve the necessary data from the context using the useContext hook.
